The school has an architect, the architects understand.
The administrative building of Avriopoint in Brno is the new headquarters of Arch.Design.
No one would expect it to hide also a mini school with everything that belongs to it - with colorful walls, imaginative furniture, a cup of toys and even a miniature playground on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, it can be visited by the children of the employees of Arch.Design.
The project-architectural company Arch.Design, from whose workshops a number of important Brno buildings came up, has counted space for its corporate mini school since the first drawings of the Avriopoint building.
It employs almost 90 people mostly in the baby boom age and it was important for women designers and architects to be able to quickly return to work.
Along with the possibility of shortened employment, the school is the benefit that Arch.Design offers its employees within the framework of the social program.
Buildings and architects so have the opportunity to combine challenging employment with child care.
The mini school was invented by Arch.Design employees themselves and with the support of the management they managed to obtain the grant from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company is funded from the European Social Fund through the Operational Programme of Human Resources and Employment and the State Budget of the Republic of Czech Republic.
Thanks to the grant funding (subsidy of CZK 2.8 million) they could buy equipment and equipment and provide qualified staff and operation for two years.
After the financial subsidy is exhausted (2 years), Arch.Design is obliged to operate a mini school for 3 years at its own cost.
The preparation of the project took one year and with the application for a grant, Economy Rating helped significantly.
Care is provided by qualified staff, children are carried out by a nurse and a teacher on a daily basis, so children can go to school without age limit, but most of them are older than 3 years old.
Because it is a "mini-school", only 5 children can be present at the same time, but more of them are replaced during the day.
The operation of the school is flexible according to the needs of the parents and the children of all employees have the same right to use the school regardless of the hierarchy of the position in the company.
Although it is individual education and care, the program filling in the mini school is comparable to the pre-school framework program.
Children are not only playing here, but they are also provided with quality teaching – from basic knowledge to preparation for school loaves, English language is also taught.
The class is equipped not only with toys, exciting games, but also with a computer that children can use.
The presence of small children directly in the company creates a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can check their child at any time and get rid of stressful situations with delayed picking up children from schoolrooms away from the workplace of the parents.
Parents use their working hours more productively.
It is not surprising that there is a natural loyal relationship between the employee and the employer.
Arch.Design is so ranked to Czech companies that offer a significant benefit in recruitment of new employees, are family-friendly and through this program it has strengthened personal marketing.
The house of bones fascinates even after 100 years. Look at the interiors of Gaudí
The roof looks like the back of an ancient yellow, the stairs resemble the spin of the dinosaur, and the balconies are open to the fish mouth.
This is the house of Casa Batlló in Barcelona by Catalan architect Antoni Gaudí.
The house, thanks to its organic shapes, is called the House of Bones.
Organic shapes, wild colors, unusual use of stone, cracks of cracks and mosaics, a facade reminding of cracks and all-present soft curves, all of this is typical for the seces of Antoni Gaudí.
The corner of the house plays dream lines, gentle colors and texture reminding nature and animals.
