In the night the entire facade of the houses sounds even more dramatic, it is enlightened so that the impression of the brightness of the colors is still strengthened.
Forcing and turning shapes in the same extent appear in the interiors.
Wood in waves copies the window frame, walls, decorative elements of the door, cracks and leaves.
The Batlló House, which stands in the Eixample district on the busy shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43, was created by the rebuilding of the house in 1877 by the architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took place for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the rich industrial Josep Batlló, initially insisted on the collapse of the old building and the construction of a completely new, but soon Gaudí's idea of an unusual and cheaper rebuilding was accepted.
The house of Casa Batlló was not designed by Antoni Gaudí.
It was designed by architect Josep Maria Jujol.
Just on his design plate created decorations for the representative apartment of the property owner and the use of the mosaic on the facade.
A number of other creators and artists worked on the facade.
The joint work on the designs of Casa Batlló started Jujola’s successful cooperation with Gaudí.
Jujol participated in Gaudí's house Casa Milá and Güell Park, where there are Gaudí's other works.
From the locals, the house soon after its completion, thanks to its organic shapes, served the surname "House of bones".
Others, due to the specific mechanism of opening windows, began to call it a "sliping house".
It is also said that on the top of the building is the sword of St. George, the patron of Catalonia.
Hidden religious motives also contain other sculpture elements of the building.
Gaudí to the house designed for his time a unique central heating system with ventilation bricks and typical fireworks.
It may seem bizarre their thirty-five-degree inclination.
In his creation, Gaudí absolutely did not respect the construction regulations at that time and did not let himself be bound by them.
At the beginning of the construction, though he obtained a building permit from the city, however, the data on the planned reconstruction was so unclean that two years later, when completed, the city council was endangered by the result and requested a correction.
For instance, the building has interfered with the pillars and the public pathway.
The correction never happened, on the contrary: just fifteen days after the call of the city part, Josep Batlló requested (and successfully obtained) permission to rent two of the highest floors of the building.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
The gallery in the second floor was a social salon and in the third floor a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The floor was rented with jewelry.
The whole six-storey house crosses a staircase, which can rise up to the roof terrace itself.
The key elements of the reconstruction were the abolition of all right angles and straight lines and their replacement with curved walls.
Gaudí also worked with the modern concept of connecting spaces.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors, and a larger society can communicate comfortably without keeping the privacy needed for more intimate conversations.
The house with Gaudí's rebuilding, in addition to the new facade, also received a non-traditional ceiling and two floors in addition.
Gaudí's game with light, blue and white glazed plates, with which the inner court is covered, and lights is impressive.
The game of two colors provides maximum light in all floors of the house.
It was enough to simply bet on the principle that white reflects the light more than dark, which, on the contrary, absorbs the sun's rays.
Casa Batlló, which was included in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund in 2005, can be visited by everyone.
In the first floor of the house, the most spacious and luxurious apartment is made available to the public.
The owners decided for this step only in 2002, on the occasion of the 100th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They stayed on the trips because they found that it was a very profitable business and, in addition, they expanded the trips to common and underground spaces, including a roof terrace.
The entrance fee is definitely not negligible, it is EUR 16.50 and students, retirees, groups and tourist card holders have a twenty-percent discount.
The amount significantly exceeds the price of entrance to other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to taste the real atmosphere of the house with the dragon towers, you need to quickly make friends with any of the residents of the factory and visit it directly at home.
