People’s monitoring devices want more and more parents, they want to carbonate their children
Fear of their own child leads more and more people to the idea of watching through GPS.
The system originally created for searching for cars can also monitor the movement of people, and thus help in such cases as the disappearance of the nine-year-old Anička Janatková.
The device is as big as a seed box, but soon it can be as big as a clock.
A number of people were scared by the case of the missing Anička and began to look for the means to better protect their children.
At the expense of violating their privacy.
“We are trying to tell everyone that it’s not a spy, but another way to reduce the likelihood of a tragedy,” says Petr Pilin from Macro Weil, one of the suppliers of tracking devices to the Czech market.
"I admit that in a certain case such devices may be misused, for example when they are placed in the bag to someone who doesn't know about it, but we have not yet met with such a case."
“Mostly it is actually purchased by customers for security reasons,” Pilin added.
According to him, the child should always know what purpose the "box" serves and how it is used in the emergency.
Children's psychologist Dana Bočková warns that if the child doesn't want to wear anything similar, he'll just get rid of it.
“Even very small children show great creativity in how to deliberately lose some things when they don’t want to be under control.”
“Great expectations were previously caused by parents’ mobile phones, but they can be turned off as well as these tracking devices,” Bočková says.
It is also controversial whether such equipment would actually help in the event of an attack.
“When it comes to a prepared kidnapping, the criminal will always ensure that the child does not have any electronics that could reveal his location.”
“It’s the phone.”
"When the tracking devices begin to expand, they will also look for them, because their sales will be supported by massive advertising."
“In this case, criminals will always be a step ahead of the police,” says the psychologist.
However, it acknowledges that similar devices can help in the event of a sudden attack by a pedophile.
According to Robert Cech from RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, even in the event of an immediate destruction of the tracking device after the attack, its presence can help.
"The device can be set to regularly send the position after a certain period of time."
"If it is damaged, at least the last position of the person concerned will be available."
"The more expensive devices have built-in and locomotives, so even if a person just slept and remained unmoving, the device will send an immediate warning with the position," says Cech.
According to him, a similar service can also be carried out by mobile phones with navigation, where it is enough to upload special software.
The problem with current tracking units lies in the fact that they are either devices similar to the stickers of the size of a seed box or smaller mobile phones.
There is always a risk of loss.
According to Pilina from Macro Weil, a device that looks like a regular digital clock is now being tested.
"This will have the greatest advantage in the fact that the potential aggressor doesn't need to know the tracking device at all."
“Of they will only know them after some time and it can give the police extra time,” he adds.
Whether tracking devices are developed into bracelets or attachments, they will still use the same technology that is used for car surveillance.
This is a combination of positioning through the GPS system (which is used by ordinary autonomous navigation) and the feature of the mobile phone that reports the current position of the vehicle.
