Longer indicator than the ring indicates lower risk of cancer
Men who have an indicator longer than the ring are exposed to a lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising conclusion of a study published on Wednesday by the British Journal of Cancer.
This may be related to the level of male hormone testosterone.
“Our findings show that the relative length of the finger can serve as a simple test of the risk of prostate cancer, especially for men under the age of 60,” said Ros Eeles, co-author of the study, a professor at the Institute for Cancer Research at the University of Warwick.
The finger could thus help to determine who men should be tested for prostate cancer, especially in combination with genetic risk or other threatening factors such as family health burden, Eeles added.
During the period 1994-2009, she followed with colleagues in the UK more than 1,500 patients with prostate cancer and simultaneously more than 3,000 healthy men.
More than half of the participants in the study had an indicator on the right hand shorter than the ring.
They had the same probability of prostate cancer as 19 percent of those whose fingers were equally long.
However, for those who had an indicator longer than the ring, this risk decreased by 33 percent, while for men under the age of sixties, it was even 87 percent.
The proportion of the length of the two fingers - formed in the prenatal period - apparently reflects the different levels of sexual hormones to which the child is exposed in the uterus.
Less testosterone corresponds to a longer indicator.
Earlier research has shown that it is testosterone that promotes the growth of prostate cancer.
Chief Czech geneticist and former chairman of the Academy of Sciences Professor Václav Pačes told CTK that he knows about this study, but he doesn’t seem to say that the relationship between finger length and cancer would be “fullly proven”.
