It is not so.
"The discovery shows that other planetary organisms may be able to take advantage of other elements that drive biochemistry and that the set of elements that we consider 'standard' may not be so absolutely necessary for life," explains Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
“This work is unusual because it shows the replacement of one element with another element in the basic biochemistry and biochemical structure,” Cockell added.
It was not a random discovery.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon from the Astrobiological Institute at NASA, who led the study, focused on Mono Lake because it shows high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically very similar elements, so she thought that the microbes that are exposed to both elements could be able to replace one by another.
“Arsenic is poisoning mainly because its chemical behavior is very similar to phosphorus.”
"The result is that organisms are very difficult to separate these elements from each other."
"But arzen is so different that it doesn't work like phosphorus.When it gets into the organism, it begins to work in biochemical processes," Anbar explained.
Scientists collect bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and expos them to an increasing concentration of arsenic, which bacteria are able to adapt and grow.
Microbes grow better with the effect of phosphorus, but since they can survive also with the arzen replacement, it increases the possibility that the form of life that uses arzen can occur naturally, either elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arzen is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, an expert microbiology assistant at the University of Florida, said that the idea of arzen that could be replaced with phosphorus is not new, but it has never been found an example on which this fact would be proved.
Arzen was more common in earlier times on Earth, she said, and so scientists speculated that it could be used by earlier forms of life.
"This suggests that there could be other ways to create life, not just the way it was created in the early period of Earth," said Foster, who was not part of the Wolfe-Simon research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Ministry of Energy and the National Institute of Health.
