Red Bull triumphs in Formula 1 with secret weapons from Siemens
The software proposes improvement in vehicles in real time.
Since Red Bull entered the Formula 1 series in 2004, his history in this exceptional world of speed is characterized by surprise and success.
At first, no one took the possibilities of this newly arriving team too seriously, and despite the upward trend from recent times, everyone was beting on the triumph of Ferrari Fernando Alonso.
Without wanting to reduce the riding capabilities of the champion, German Sebastian Vettel, or the possibilities of the Renault engine that drives his car, the legend - the "secret weapon" that the multinational Siemens has placed in the hands of the Red Bull, has been born in the Formula 1 world to make it a winning team.
In fact, this is a powerful simulating software that the German company launched in 2007 for very distant automotive sports purposes.
The so-called PLM, this powerful software device, was used to design assembly lines in manufacturing plants around the world, in energy plants and for high precision devices.
It aims to faithfully reproduce the product or simulate the process before it is actually created, thus avoiding unnecessary errors and expenses.
The PLM has facilitated the development of the Canon camera, Sukhoi aircraft, and Nissan’s most famous utility vehicles.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of the industrial division of Siemens, explains that the use of this software device allowed the Red Bull team to carry out "in a few hours, in almost real time" modifications and improvements that are otherwise detected during races and tests.
Russwurm says that in 1992, the stages employed an average of 10 technicians who were able to perform a maximum of three or four improvements in one period.
The Red Bull team is currently working on 180 young highly qualified professionals equipped with powerful information technology, who analyze and design every type of modification of racing vehicles.
The head of Siemens explained that the PLM software is able to analyze and improve all elements of the Red Bull racing vehicles except the engine, for which Renault is fully responsible.
Materials, fuel, aerodynamics and safety elements are modified.
Changes can be translated from virtual reality to reality in less than 24 hours thanks to advanced laser production systems and highly technologically advanced autoclaves.
The only limit of this technical capacity is the amount of $40 million representing the maximum that each Formula 1 team can spend for each period to improve its competitiveness.
Red Bull has set up about 50 km from London a high-end technology plant to design and manufacture its racing cars.
These are two buildings that are limited to visitors – especially to journalists.
Everything that is happening here is considered a "big secret".
The list of participants in this project has 580 people including two pilots - champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
The Red Bull champion in Formula 1 is Sebastian Vettel.
Behind the immeasurable technological resources that the brand of energy drinks has put into its participation in racing circles, there are other protagonists, whose help is invaluable, and at the same time no one knows them.
Production technology chief Steve Nevey claims that five years ago it was possible to say that advances in vehicle research and development contributed to the victory of 50% and the rest was the merit of drivers.
Currently, this ratio has changed and technology is worth the achievements of 85%, while pilots contribute from 15%.
Nevey acknowledges that Vettel or Webber will never be replaced by computing, as they are “unpredictable gladiators.”
