Zapatero and the Red German Line
Berlin has decided to maintain the euro, but has set the conditions for the whole Union.
The tensions on the markets provoked a double government response.
On the one hand, José Luis Zapatero proposed new adaptation measures, from the reduction of taxes for small and medium enterprises, through the regulation of private mediation agencies or the abolition of 426 euros for unemployed without benefits, to the privatization of 49% AENA (Spanish Airports and Air Traffic Management - note. translation), the manager of Barajas and El Prat airports and 30% state lottery.
Vice-President Elena Salgad, with the support of former Prime Minister Felipe González, on the other hand, joined the criticism of Chancellor Angela Merkel because of her responsibility to trigger the current crisis.
How to interpret this motivation?
It should be said in advance that Merkel’s opinion is not a mistake in her communication policy.
On the contrary, this is another point in the complex process of redefining the euro.
And here Germany has a radically new vision of what its future is to be, which affects the idea of observing the old traditions, which is held by a large portion of the other members.
In the face of European resistance, Germany is beginning to speculate about three possible ways to get out of the crisis.
The first of them is a strong euro zone, which would be part of Germany, but also, for example, Austria or the Netherlands, while the southern states would leave the currency zone.
The second is the return to March - although now it may seem as a sci-fi, this version has broad public support, approaching 50% of the population.
The third option is, according to the German proposals, the re-working of the euro with greater macroeconomic supervision, budget strictness, penalties for the guilty states, possible delays of payments for some of them, and with the expansion of possible regulatory costs to the private sector.
The German position is clear and has been defined for some time, so there is no space for the pulls now.
First, when the International Monetary Fund (IMF) and the European Commission stimulated deficits in 2009, the German government pulled out a constitutional reform to prevent them from 2016.
This was the first sign of contradiction between what Germany considered right (financial rigidity and public finance stability plans) and what its European partners, including France, practiced.
The second showed this Central European country when Merkel painfully extended the decision to save Greece.
It was already the subject of sharp criticism, but the truth is that the political consensus in Germany and the public opinion, which was also published, were strongly against the rescue of Greece.
Finally, in the last days of October, Merkel again appeared with a clear opinion when she called for a reform of the EU conventions so that it would be possible to rescue a member state and at the same time that private borrows had the obligation to bear part of the costs.
This opinion was interpreted as anti-European, as it accelerated the Irish crisis and everything else.
However, its proposal, although in a slightly mild form, has been approved, and in the coming months we should follow the Union reform process, which should allow these measures from 2013.
Germany has drawn a red line that it does not intend to cross.
