U.S. changes visa rules
People will have to contact the Visa Applicant Services Centre even before the interview at the Consular Department; the costs will be lower and the waiting time will be shorter.
From January 10, 2011, the process of visa examination at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will be changed.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will have to contact the Visa Application Services Centre (in short from ASC) even before the interview at the Consular Department.
The ASC staff will remove the applicant’s biometric information and the information will be assessed by the Consular Department before the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages, among which are:
The total cost of the visa processing will be lower, there will no longer be a fee for the meeting agreement, the second for the processing of the application and the other for the delivery of the document by the transport service.
The applicant will only pay a single fee that will cover all three services.
The current tariff will remain unchanged: the amount corresponding to $140 per tourist visa, $150 per visa with application (including temporary workers visa) and $390 per visa for traders and investors.
People who want to renew their visa will not have to undergo an interview with a consular official, but will only contact the nearest ASC, where they will submit their documents and their fingerprints will be taken.
Since biometric information will be removed in the ASC, applicants who will require a second meeting with an interview at the Consular Department will spend a shorter time here than in the past.
Likewise, those who will apply for a visa at the consulates in Ciudad Juárez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay an extra fee for the service of $26.
For more information about the new procedure for the visa application, visit the following website http://mexico.usembassy.gov/boletines/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
