World Plan for the Restoration of Lighting
The United Nations proposed a plan to restore domestic lighting, commercial lighting and industrial spaces in 100 countries in order to a greenhouse effect limit (GES), which corresponds to one-third of the further limitation to be achieved to stabilize the climate of the planet from now to 2020.
This ambitious plan is at the stage of large specific projects that the United Nations wants to implement in Cancún to compensate for the lack of difficult to implement commitments to reduction on the side of industrially developed countries.
According to the plan submitted yesterday, if the burned lamps, which monopolize another 50 to 70% of the market, will be replaced with fluocompact lamps or, even better, with electroluminiscent diodes (DEL or "LED" in English), the substantial amount of 1.8 billion tons (Gt) of GES emissions on the planet generated due to lighting would disrupt.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of world emissions.
This is equivalent to 70% of emissions from a car park throughout the planet.
In Copenhagen last year, large countries with a significant share of emissions such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, have engaged in voluntary reduction plans that should allow global GES emissions to decrease from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will need to be reduced from this balance even more 5 Gt to a stabilization of climate warming at 2 degrees Celsius by 2020 so that it can be excluded that it does not get out of control.
In burned lights 95% of energy is dispersed in the form of heat and the rest, i.e. 5%, is a product of light.
With fluocompact lights, energy consumption is reduced by 75% and with new DEL lights, we reduce this consumption twice.
Fluocompact lamps will last an average of 6000 to 10,000 hours.
The new DEL lamps, which was introduced this week into production by Philips - this company allegedly participated in the UN study - have an estimated life of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than the burned lamp, giving us an idea of possible savings with a replacement plan that would be applied in 100 countries.
All of these new lights can also work with reostates and radiate less heat.
They do not contain mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations to fluocompact lamps because they contain mercury and need to be classified as hazardous waste, which is still impossible in developing countries unless manufacturers set up collection stations.
However, as the report reports, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the fluocompact lamp, but rather the thermal coal power plants that release a lot of mercury needed to produce electricity burned in burned lamps.
Only in the United States, these centrals circulate 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report also detailed the profits that each country would get from this international program.
For example, Indonesia would save a billion dollars a year on the purchase of electricity and eight million tons of CO2, which is equivalent to 3.5 thermal power plants, whose construction would cost 2.5 billion dollars.
