Climate: how France hacked its financing promises
A year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to try to comply with the promises of rapidly unblocked financing (the so-called fast-start financing) implemented by developed countries.
The great French hackers were revealed.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries pledged to provide $30 billion in 2010-2012.
The European Union promised €7.2 billion for three years and France €1.26 billion (i.e. €420 million annually).
At the start of COP16, the EU brought a big ass to convince its partners about the reality of its commitment to fast-start financing: a report that clarifies the actions of its Member States, a press conference, a grand side event, the distribution of brochures...
Transparent operations unprecedented and appreciated for their real value: developed countries and civil society would want all developed countries and civil society to do them equally and with the same degree of accuracy.
The EU announces that it has released €2.2 billion in 2010, leading it to the right path to fulfill its €7.2 billion promise in 2012.
But if we focus on the details, we will find that things are much more complicated.
According to the Copenhagen Agreement, these funds are "new and additional" to ensure that the increased burden is implemented without prejudice to the Public Development Aid.
Unfortunately, there is no consensus in what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission proposed a harmonisation, some Member States, including France, blocked the process.
Today, everyone will choose the reference that is best suited to him.
For example, the European Commission regarded 2009 as a reference: international financing wasined and it still adds 150 million to the three-year fast-start financing title.
Other countries have selected similar references with annual payment deadlines or with deadlines at the level of public development aid.
France, on the contrary, considers that the financing of "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words,there is no reference to the expenditure of the previous periods or to the global level of the public development aid d'Aide publique au développement.
In particular, the total amount of support from France to developing countries can remain unchanged (or even decrease), to comply with its commitment to financing "new and additional" countries.
Another crucial element is the division into gifts and loans.
There is no rule yet and everyone chooses his own method of calculation.
Some, such as France, consider that 1€ borrowed is equal to 1€ donated.
Evidently, it is hard to prove: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be proven for some investments that are profitable (often these are projects associated with emissions reduction, consisting in more efficient technologies), it is foolish to present one euro we get, as an equivalent to one euro we give... , we should not understand it from the title of our obligations, but as the price of the loan for the borrower country (i.e. the equivalent of the interest rate).
But France can only give the following justification: it “respects” its 420 million euro commitment, making it 91,5% loan (389.8 million euros) and 8,5% donations (36.1 million euros) – see the EU document to verify it yourself.
It is the only country in the EU that uses such a loan.
Germany demanded 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia (including others) comply with their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the absolute majority of the European Union gives €1 in the framework of fulfilling its promise, France gives only 10 centimeters and considers this effort comparable.
A beautiful keylogger!
In summary, with its "fast start" financing, France operates with a double shielding: on the one hand with the development of shares in time and on the other hand with a real financial burden.
Although it is only $36.1 million, it can convince that it is $420 million "new and additional" in connection with its promises.
The manipulation of the Minister of Finance (because it seems that although it is Bercy who made such decisions) could have a double negative impact, at the same time within the EU (why would Member States continue to donate when it is enough to borrow?) and during negotiations, because developing countries are not completely naive...
The chapter of premature financing is just a small, relatively short-term issue in relation to a series of climate discussions.
But it could be a grain of sand in an enormous machine like the UNFCCC.
Hopefully this is not our case.
Whatever it is, it is necessary to draw knowledge from this first year of premature financing.
First of all, France should announce a change in its way of accounting for 2011 and 2012, in the spirit of compliance with its obligations and fairness and justice towards other European Union countries.
But above all, France should avoid discussions about long-term funding deposits (an other important chapter currently discussed): we will not escape the question of "additivity" or how to bill loans.
France should change its attitude to become as progressive with these deposits as it is with others.
Therefore, hopes are all placed in the new Minister of the Environment, Ms Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancún next week.
The surprising announcement of France’s fast start and its vision of “additivity” and the use of loans could trigger an increase in the level of international confidence necessary to make it possible to move forward in the discussions.
